#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rst:315
msgid ""
"What if we want to change a value stored in a variable? We need to use an "
"assignment operator."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rst:318
msgid ""
"For example, take a look at this code. It prints the number ``4`` twice. "
"First, we assign ``3`` to ``x``. Then, every time we print we add one to "
"``x``. We *aren't* changing the original value of ``x``, so we don't print "
"``4`` and then ``5``. The variable ``x`` only holds the number ``3``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rst:324
msgid ""
"# Add one to x, but the number x holds does not change.\n"
"x = 3\n"
"print(x + 1)\n"
"print(x + 1)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rst:331
msgid ""
"Take a look at this example. This example prints ``3``. It *does* add ``1`` "
"to ``x``. But it does nothing with the result. We don't print it. Just like "
"the prior example, the number in ``x`` doesn't change."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rst:335
msgid ""
"# Add one to x, but the number x holds still does not change.\n"
"x = 3\n"
"x + 1\n"
"print(x)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rst:342
msgid ""
"Now look at this example. We use the assignment operator. We store into "
"``x`` the result of ``x + 1``. This *does* increase the value stored in "
"``x`` and therefore we print out a ``4``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rst:346
msgid ""
"x = 3\n"
"x = x + 1\n"
"print(x)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rst:354
msgid ""
"It can be confusing to learn when to use ``x + 1`` and when to use ``x = x +"
" 1``. Remember, the former does *not* change the value of ``x``."
msgstr ""

