"Because statements like ``x = x + 1`` are so common, we can shorten this "
"using the ``+=`` assignment operator. Examine this code to see how it works:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rst:383
msgid ""
"# This works, and prints \"3\"\n"
"x = 3\n"
"print(x)\n"
"\n"
"# Make x bigger by one using the regular\n"
"# assignment operator.\n"
"x = x + 1\n"
"print(x)\n"
"\n"
"# Make x bigger by one, using the +=\n"
"# assignment operator.\n"
"x += 1\n"
"print(x)\n"
"\n"
"# Make x smaller by five using the -=\n"
"# operator.\n"
"x -= 5\n"
"print(x)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rst:405
msgid ""
"Remember, if you want to increase or decrease a variable, you need to use an"
" assignment operator."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rst:407
msgid ""
"Oh, and a common mistake is to mix the ``+`` and ``+=`` operator as shown in"
" this example. It doesn't just add one to x, it doubles x and adds one."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rst:410
msgid ""
"# This doubles x, and then adds one.\n"
"# Probably not what the programmer intended.\n"
"x += x + 1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rst:417
msgid "Using Expressions In Function Calls"
msgstr "Verwendung von Funktionsaufrufen in Ausdrücken"

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rst:419
msgid ""
"Expressions are not limited to assignment statements. We can use expressions"
" as parameters in function calls. This can be useful when you need a quick "
"calculation. For example, what if we want to draw a circle in the center of "
"the screen?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rst:425
msgid ""
"By creating variables for the height and width of the screen, we can set the"
" screen size, and also do a quick calculation to find the screen center. In "
"this example we use constant variables for the screen width and height. Then"
" use some math to calculate the center of the screen."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rst:431
msgid "Calculating the center of the screen"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rst:431
msgid ""
"import arcade\n"
"\n"
"SCREEN_WIDTH = 800\n"
"SCREEN_HEIGHT = 600\n"
"\n"
"arcade.open_window(SCREEN_WIDTH, SCREEN_HEIGHT, \"Drawing Example\")\n"
"\n"
"arcade.set_background_color(arcade.color.WHITE)\n"
"\n"
"arcade.start_render()\n"
"\n"
"# Instead of this:\n"
"# arcade.draw_circle_filled(400, 300, 50, arcade.color.FOREST_GREEN)\n"
"# do this:\n"
"arcade.draw_circle_filled(SCREEN_WIDTH / 2,\n"
"                          SCREEN_HEIGHT / 2,\n"
"                          50,\n"
"                          arcade.color.FOREST_GREEN)\n"
"\n"
"arcade.finish_render()\n"
"arcade.run()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rst:458
msgid ""
"The great thing about this is that the variables which control the screen "
"size can be changed, and the circle will automatically be re-centered. Had "
"we simply coded (400, 300) as the center, we'd need to go and change that "
"number as well. Perhaps not a big deal with a small program, but as our "
"programs get larger it saves a lot of time."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rst:465
msgid "Order of Operations"
msgstr "Rangfolge der Operatoren"

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rstNone
msgid ".. image:: chapters/07_expressions/calculator_2.svg"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rst:471
msgid ""
"Python will evaluate expressions using the same *order of operations* you "
"learned in math. For example this expression does not correctly calculate "
"the average:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rst:475
msgid "average = 90 + 86 + 71 + 100 + 98 / 5"
msgstr "average = 90 + 86 + 71 + 100 + 98 / 5"

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rst:479
msgid ""
"The first operation to be calculated is ``98 / 5``, rather than adding up "
"the numbers. That is, the computer calculates this equation instead:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rst:482
msgid "90+86+71+100+\\frac{98}{5}"
msgstr "90+86+71+100+\\frac{98}{5}"

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rst:486
msgid "What we need is an equation where the division happens last:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rst:488
msgid "\\dfrac{90+86+71+100+98}{5}"
msgstr "\\dfrac{90+86+71+100+98}{5}"

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rst:492
msgid ""
"By using parentheses around the addition in our code, this problem can be "
"fixed:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rst:494
msgid "average = (90 + 86 + 71 + 100 + 98) / 5"
msgstr "average = (90 + 86 + 71 + 100 + 98) / 5"

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rst:499
msgid "Printing Variables"
msgstr "Ausgabe von Variablen"

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rstNone
msgid ".. image:: chapters/07_expressions/printer.svg"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rst:505
msgid ""
"How can you print variables and text together? Say you've got a variable "
"``answer`` and you want to print it. Based on what we've learned so far, you"
" can do this code:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rst:508
msgid ""
"answer = \"bananas\"\n"
"print(answer)"
msgstr ""
"answer = \"bananas\"\n"
"print(answer)"

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rst:513
msgid ""
"But that just prints out ``bananas`` on a line by itself. Not very "
"descriptive. What if we wanted:"
msgstr ""
"Aber das gibt nur ``bananas`` auf einer Zeile alleine aus. Nicht wirklich "
"anschaulich. Was wenn wir haben wollten:"

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rst:516
msgid "The answer is bananas"
msgstr "The answer is bananas"

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rst:520
msgid ""
"You can combine the answer with the additional text by using a comma. Here's"
" an example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rstNone
msgid ".. image:: chapters/07_expressions/banana.svg"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rst:527
msgid ""
"answer = \"bananas\"\n"
"print(\"The answer is\", answer)"
msgstr ""
"answer = \"bananas\"\n"
"print(\"The answer is\", answer)"

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rst:532
msgid ""
"That example was better. But it is missing punctuation. This code attempts "
"to add a period at the end:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rst:535
msgid ""
"answer = \"bananas\"\n"
"print(\"The answer is\", answer, \".\")"
msgstr ""
"answer = \"bananas\"\n"
"print(\"The answer is\", answer, \".\")"

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rst:540
msgid ""
"Unfortunately, it doesn't work quite right. We get an extra space before the"
" period:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rst:543
msgid "The answer is bananas ."
msgstr "The answer is bananas ."

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rst:547
msgid ""
"The ``,`` adds a space when we use it in a ``print`` statement. We don't "
"always want that. We can instead use a ``+`` sign as shown in this example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rst:550
msgid ""
"answer = \"bananas\"\n"
"print(\"The answer is\" + answer + \".\")"
msgstr ""
"answer = \"bananas\"\n"
"print(\"The answer is\" + answer + \".\")"

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rst:555
msgid "That gets rid of all the spaces:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rst:557
msgid "The answer isbananas."
msgstr "The answer isbananas."

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rst:561
msgid ""
"So we need to add a space INSIDE the quotes where we want it as shown here:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rst:563
msgid ""
"answer = \"bananas\"\n"
"print(\"The answer is \" + answer + \".\")"
msgstr ""
"answer = \"bananas\"\n"
"print(\"The answer is \" + answer + \".\")"

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rst:568
msgid ""
"That works until you try an to print a variable that holds a number instead "
"of text. Try this example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rst:571
msgid ""
"answer = 42\n"
"print(\"The answer is \" + answer + \".\")"
msgstr ""
"answer = 42\n"
"print(\"The answer is \" + answer + \".\")"

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rst:576
msgid ""
"That code generates a brand new error we haven't seen yet, a ``TypeError``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rst:578
msgid ""
"Traceback (most recent call last):\n"
"  File \"C:/arcade_book/test.py\", line 2, in <module>\n"
"    print(\"The answer is \" + answer + \".\")\n"
"TypeError: can only concatenate str (not \"int\") to str"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rst:585
msgid ""
"What is the problem? The computer doesn't know how to put text and numbers "
"together. If you add two *numbers* ``20 + 20`` you get ``40``. If you add "
"two *strings* ``\"20\" + \"20\"`` you get ``\"2020\"``, but the computer has"
" no idea what to do with a combo of text and numbers. So the fix is to use "
"the ``str`` function which converts the number to a string (text). Here's an"
" example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rst:594
msgid ""
"answer = 42\n"
"print(\"The answer is \" + str(answer) + \".\")"
msgstr ""
"answer = 42\n"
"print(\"The answer is \" + str(answer) + \".\")"

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rst:599
msgid ""
"Yes, this is a bit complex. But wait! There's an easier way! We can print "
"variables using a *formatted string*. Later we will spend a whole chapter on"
" formatted strings, but here's an example to get started."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rst:603
msgid ""
"answer = 42\n"
"print(f\"The answer is {answer}.\")"
msgstr ""
"answer = 42\n"
"print(f\"The answer is {answer}.\")"

#: ../../source/chapters/07_expressions/expressions.rst:608
msgid ""
"Note this example starts the string with an ``f`` before the quote, and the "
"variable we want to print goes in curly braces. This is the way I recommend "
"printing variables. Again, we'll cover it in more detail in a later chapter."
msgstr ""

